This paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category as it deals with search engine result pages and their evaluation. The paper also discusses user behavior and satisfaction, which suggests that it could also belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of natural language processing techniques, which could place it in the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category. The paper also discusses the visual layout of search engine result pages, which could place it in the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CY) sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions the use of one-box answers and side panels, which suggests that it could also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
